title: RichRap's 3DR - BIGGER Top and Bottom Extensions

description.text:
Inspired by Pablogil - I've modelled up some even BIGGERER(!) Extensions to RichRaps wonderful 3DR.
As used in http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:203893!
(Blatant self plug) These should be printable on any standard sized RepRap bed (190mmX190mm) and will increase the cylindrical print volume of the 3DR to 'about' 260mm Diameter (assuming you increase your rod lengths appropriately) Included is a 3D model of a fully assembled 3DR frame, for easy visual reference of where these fit.
(probably not worth thinking about printing it - it's just for reference) **Work In Progress - I've not finished modelling the top section to have compatible electronics mounts for ALL standard. elec' boards (and given how fast they multiply, I probably never will...)
  • as it stands at this point, the mounts should fit almost all Sanguino based boards at 4 points.
    RAMPS (based), Gen7. Melzi, MEGA, Beagles and Smoothies -(plus Various others) should all fit to two or more mount points, (Which is usually more than adequate mounting) - so further tweaking is probably to come...**
    • EDIT: V2 uploaded with stronger electronics mounts, or the option for no mounts at all...

These are extensions to RichRaps Mavellous 3DR Delta RepRap,
They sit between each top and bottom 'corner' to extend the overall printable area.
Make sure you accommodate for extra wire and rod length where necessary...

comments.text:
Richraps' Generally suggested quick calculation for rod lengths is
0.8 x Horizontal distance between the vertical posts (Vp). [which by my tape measure is ~330mm]
Other Delta designs go off 2xR

description.text:
This is version 2 of my upgraded G2s (version 1 http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:2020086) - basically a full overhaul of everything but the top/bottom plates and the linear rods. It is a continuation of trying to make my G2s the best it can be (not really a G2s anymore at this point i guess!).

Quick summary of upgrades:

  1. Custom Carriages.
  2. Magnetic Arms.
  3. Custom Effector.
  4. E3D Cyclops 2in-1out Hotend.
  5. Part Cooling Fan.
  6. Greg’s Wade Geared Extruders.
  7. Optical Endstops.
  8. Duet Wifi electronics.
  9. 7” PanelDue interface.
  10. Increased usable print diameter and height (Ø200mm x 210mm height).

Issues with the G2s:

  1. Motion slop
    a. Delta arms have play and design limits ability to accurately calibrate length.
    b. 2 bearing carriages have excessive play and torque from the arms causes them to pitch up, having significant influence on the end effector.
    c. Design of the stock end effector has the effector center of mass below the rod link locations, which will cause effector tilt and unwanted movement during acceleration/jerk moves.

  2. Hotend performance
    a. Stock hotend is difficult to level and reduces usable bed size.
    b. Dual nozzle configuration suffers when effector tilt occurs.
    c. No part cooling fan included.

  3. Extruder performance
    a. The direct drive extruder is ok, but the hobbing on the drive gear is a bit shallow, and the force on the filament could be a bit stronger to handle higher print and retraction speeds. It is likely ok for stock setup, but will not be sufficient once other components are upgraded.

  4. Probing performance
    a. Microswitch probe must be manually deployed, sometimes binds in bore causing unrepeatable measures.

  5. Electronics
    a. GT2560 board is not capable of driving the axes past ~80mm/sec. Studdering occurs at higher speeds. Interpolation is broken into segments that are too large for higher speed movement.
    b. Included limit switches are acceptable, but not repeatable enough to make probing and really dialing in the delta parameters worth it, as each G28 throws it off here or there.

  6. Lighting
    a. None!

My solutions to those issues:

  1. Motion slop
    a. Haydn’s magnetic arms (http://www.blueeaglelabs.com/products/haydns-carbon-fiber-arms-with-cnc-precision-machined-delrin-sockets). Mine came accurate in length to .01mm.
    b. Complete redesign of carriages to accept 4 LMU-N10 bearings (https://us.misumi-ec.com/vona2/detail/110300026540/?HissuCode=LMU-N10) and the mag arms. Carriages work with stock microswitch endstops or optical endstop upgrade.
    c. Rather that adapt the stock effector to fit the mag arms, I designed a new one. This effector design is much more modular and makes creating addons easy.
    d. With below hotend, center of mass is aligned to mag arm spheres to resist effector tilt.

  2. Hotend performance
    a. 2in-1out hotend (http://e3d-online.com/Cyclops), retain dual extrusion ability but without the loss of bed area or difficulty in levelling.
    b. Influence of effector tilt is greatly reduced with a single nozzle centered on the effector.
    c. Integrated part cooling fan into hotned mount.

  3. Extruder performance
    a. I ordered 2 of the Greg's Wade Extruder hardware kit at (https://www.ultibots.com/gregs-wade-extruder-hardware-kit/), and printed 2 sets of the extruder parts - 1 regular and 1 mirrored (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:18379). In order to fit in the location of the original, you need to mirror one of the extruders. In doing so you need to reverse the hobbed bolt - to get the hobbed portion of the bolt aligned with the feeder tube, you'll need the included spacer. In addition, the attached gear has a deeper relief to accept the bolt in the mirrored extruder. Any questions on this let me know.

  4. Probing performance
    a. Force Sensitive Resistor (FSR) probing system (https://www.ultibots.com/fsr-kit/).
    b. FSR’s live under the bed and probing is done directly when the nozzle contacts the bed. They are not affected by choice of bed (glass/non-conductive/etc).

  5. Electronics
    a. Duet Wifi (https://duet3d.com/DuetWifi). Tons of processing HP to deal with the calculations needed to drive a delta bot. Firmware configuration is very easy and powerful. Program transfer and machine control via WiFi through the web interface is awesome. Interpolating at 300mm/s with no issues.
    b. PanelDue (https://miscsolutions.wordpress.com/paneldue/). 7” touchscreen that allows easy control of the bot, plus a nice menu to execute custom macros for filament loading/probing/etc.
    c. Optical endstops (http://www.ebay.ca/itm/282247383661). Plenty on eBay if you search “RAMPS 1.4 Optical Endstop”. Enstops are shielded from sunlight interference in a protective housing.

  6. Lighting
    a. Enclosure mounted LED’s for overall interior lighting.
    b. Effector mounted LED’s for part lighting.
    c. LED brightness controllable by M code.

Printer:

Flashforge Creator Pro

Rafts:

Doesn't Matter

Supports:

Doesn't Matter

Notes:

Effector parts = ABS, PETG, PC....anything with higher Tg than PLA. I printed mine from Nylon.
Everything else = PLA or similar for stiffness.

Included:

All the STL's needed, as well a STEP model of the entire printer assembly.

description.text:
Pour les 9 ans de ma fille, un gâteau Platform 9 s’imposait….

Temps d’impression 3D* : 3h40
Temps de réalisation : 40min (hors préparation du cake design)
Niveau de difficulté : Débutant.

For additional information, please visit : www.buse-toi-meme.com

Le Matériel :

3,5m de PLA
1 cake design recouvert de pâte à sucre blanche
1 colorant alimentaire or en bombe
1 colorant alimentaire brique
1 pinceau
De la pâte à sucre de couleur Brique
1 éponge propre
Du sirop de glucose
De l’alcool

La Réalisation :

Réalisation des emportes pièces :

  1. Téléchargez les fichiers .stl sur votre ordinateur : busetoimeme-impression3d-HarryPotter-Platform9.
  2. Ouvrir le(s) fichier(s) dans votre logiciel d’impression (Cura, CraftWare…).
  3. Réglez les paramètres spécifiques suivants ou choisissez le mode qualité standard prédéfini par votre logiciel:

Vitesse d’impression : 50 mm/s
Type de support : Aucun
Type d’accroche sur le plateau : Aucun

4.Enregistrez votre Gcode

Préparation de la machine et impression :

1.Insérez du filament PLA
2.Vérifiez les attributs de l’imprimante comme suit :

T° buse : 210°C
T° plateau : 60°C

3.Mettez une fine couche de colle sur le plateau (colle papier blanche en bâton – pas la peine d’avoir de la colle spéciale – Un plateau propre avec une fine couche de colle posée de façon uniforme permet d’avoir un meilleur état de surface au final.)
4.Chargez le fichier GCode dans l’imprimante et lancez l’impression. 5.Récupérez les objets à la fin de l’impression.

Mise en œuvre :
1.Nettoyez au liquide vaisselle ou à l’alcool vos impressions pour y enlever les microbes et les traces éventuelles de colle. Laissez sécher.
2.Étalez sur une épaisseur de 3-4 mm la pâte à sucre
3.Appliquer les emporte-pièces. Détachez les parties non nécessaires. Vous pouvez vous aider d’un cure-dent pour détacher la pâte à sucre de l’emporte pièce.
4.Appliquez le colorant en spray sur les chiffres, le rond et le cadre. Utilisez un pinceau pour les lettres du « HOGWARD EXPRESS ».
5.Une fois secs, assemblez les chiffres et le cercle sur le grand rond. Collez avec un peu de sirop de glucose. Appliquez le tampon « ANS » entre le 3 et le 4. Assemblez le cadre rectangulaire autour du rectangle « HOGWARD EXPRESS ». Laissez durcir à l’air libre (1 ou 2 jours si vous avez le temps).
6.Mélangez un peu de sirop de glucose légèrement chauffé avec un peu d’alcool et du colorant brique dans une soucoupe. Découpez un rectangle aux bords inégaux de la taille d’une brique dans votre éponge, et trempez-le dans le mélange. Appliquez l’éponge essorée sur la pâte à sucre du gâteau en faisant des lignes de façon à donner l’aspect d’un mur de brique. Retrempez l’éponge après quelques motifs de brique. Laissez séchez (1- 2h environ).
7.Positionnez les décorations sur le gâteau et les fixant avec de la colle alimentaire ou du sirop de glucose.
8.N’oubliez pas les bougies !!

Buses :-))

title: Tarot gimbal mounts for the Phantom quad

description.text:
I needed a way to mount the arm of the Tarot to the anti-vibration plate on the Phantom quadcopter, above the anti-vibration plate. The arm is so long that the GoPro3 would hit the ground otherwise.
I also made a mount for the controller board that friction fits the roll control brushless motor.

Makerbot Replicator (1)
MakerWare 2.3.0.4
Printed with clear ABS;
50% fill
4 shells
.2mm layer The Board Bracket needs to be printed with supports and rotated so the 4 cylinders are on the build plate. This makes for a smooth connection to the roll control brushless motor. I designed the 4 cylinders to accept a #2 1/4 screw from McMaster.com. It's a small fastener but does a great job. The drawing was done in Cubify Invent. Good, easy, and only $50

description.text:
This started off as a custom-fit tray to keep my iPhone from sliding off a lap desk, but I made it customizable so you can use it for all kinds of things -- even a box with a fitted lid by creating two trays with no cutaways the right sizes to fit snugly.

For a phone holder/tray:

  • Measure your phone (object or inside dimensions you want)

    • measurements set the inner dimensions of the tray
    • Use the 'gap' parameter to adjust the fit

  • The cutaways are optional and adjustable,

    • if you want a side, top/bottom or base to be solid, set the cutaway to '0'
    • you can also set the percentage of cutaway for each (value between 0-1, 75% = 0.75)

description.text:
I love sculpting Tudor roses and ages ago, I made this piece as a test object for personal use, as you can see from the pictures. Someone requested I upload it, so here you go..

There are 3 variants:

loubie_tudor_rose_simple_test.stl

This is about 6.5cm wide and I use this to test "showy" or "posh" filament because the shapes show off colours, metallic content or texture really well. In the example, it is showcasing Proto-pasta's beautiful Glitter-Flake HTPLA.

loubie_tudor_rose_pendant.stl
loubie_tudor_rose_chain_bead.stl

I used this to test a resin printer with every intention of getting it cast in gold. Never got around to it:-/ If someone does cast this then let me know - I want:-)

loubie_tudor_rose_test_for_casting.stl

This is a simplified version of the file which I used to do my first mold and cast in polyurethane resin.

It is a good design to test clarity of print an to showcase filament.

I hope you enjoy it and find it useful!

PS Designed in Blender

description.text:
L’imprimante 3d ne va pas, ou du moins pas encore, vous imprimer votre cake design comme sorti du four. Par contre c’est l’outil magique pour la personnalisation de vos cakes design.

J’ai préparé un gâteau à étages de 2 couleurs (rouge et jaune pour la maison Gryffondor) sur la base d’un Molly cake recouvert de pâte à sucre blanche et fourré de ganache au chocolat. La recette du Molly cake est tirée d’un site que j’aime beaucoup et où les étapes sont très bien expliquées. Vous y trouverez d’ailleurs toutes les étapes pour réaliser un parfait design cake : MyCake.fr

Informations :

Temps d’impression 3D* : environ 3h (le temps dépend du nombre de lettres) pour le pic + 35 min pour le tampon-empreinte
Temps de réalisation : 30min (hors préparation du cake design)
Niveau de difficulté : Débutant avec connaissance de base de 3D.

Tous les détails sur : www.buse-toi-meme.com

Le Matériel :

Environ 2,5m (dépend du nombre de lettres) de PLA Noir ou mieux du nGen (ce filament a un aspect + brillant que le PLA)
0,5m de PLA pour le tampon
1 cake design recouvert de pâte à sucre
1 colorant alimentaire en bombe
1 pinceau
Du scotch et du papier
Des accessoires en chocolat ou pâte à sucre pour rajouter sur le gâteau

A. La Réalisation du texte à piquer sur le gâteau :

CRÉATION DU FICHIER 3D :

  1. Téléchargez une police Harry Potter sur dafont.com par exemple.
    1. Écrivez le texte que vous souhaitez dans votre logiciel3D. Rapprocher chaque lettre l’une de l’autre de façon à ce que chaque lettre soit attaché à une autre lettre. Au bas d’une lettre, ajoutez un rectangle ou un éclair. C’est la partie qui sera plantée dans le gâteau. Prenez garde à ce qu’il y ai au moins 0,5mm de matière entre 2 lignes de tracé (par exemple entre les 2 trous du B de Birthday).
    2. Extrudez de 2 mm
    3. Enregistrez votre fichier en .stl et ouvrez le dans votre logiciel d’impression (Cura, CraftWare…).
  2. Réglez les paramètres spécifiques suivants ou choisissez le mode qualité standard prédéfini par votre logiciel:

Vitesse d’impression : 50 mm/s
Type de support : Aucun
Type d’accroche sur le plateau : Aucun

  1. Enregistrez votre Gcode

PREPARATION DE LA MACHINE ET IMPRESSION :

  1. Insérez le filament PLA noir ou nGen
    1. Vérifiez les attributs de l’imprimante comme suit :

PLA : T° buse : 210°C – T° plateau : 60°C
nGen : T° buse : 220°C – T° plateau : 75°C

  1. Mettez une fine couche de colle sur le plateau (colle papier blanche en bâton – pas la peine d’avoir de la colle spéciale – Un plateau propre avec une fine couche de colle posée de façon uniforme permet d’avoir un meilleur état de surface au final.)
    1. Chargez le fichier GCode dans l’imprimante et lancez l’impression.
    2. Récupérez les objets à la fin de l’impression

B. La Réalisation du tampon HP :

PRÉPARATION DU FICHIER :

1.Télécharger le fichier .stl sur votre ordinateur : busetoimeme-impression3d-HarryPotter-Tampon.
2.Ouvrir le(s) fichier(s) dans votre logiciel d’impression (Cura, CraftWare…).
3.Réglez les paramètres spécifiques suivants ou choisissez le mode qualité standard prédéfini par votre logiciel:

Vitesse d’impression : 50 mm/s
Type de support : Aucun
Type d’accroche sur le plateau : Aucun

4.Enregistrez votre Gcode

PREPARATION DE LA MACHINE ET IMPRESSION:

  1. Insérez du filament PLA
    1. Vérifiez les attributs de l’imprimante comme suit :

T° buse : 210°C
T° plateau : 60°C

3.Mettez une fine couche de colle sur le plateau (colle papier blanche en bâton – pas la peine d’avoir de la colle spéciale – Un plateau propre avec une fine couche de colle posée de façon uniforme permet d’avoir un meilleur état de surface au final.)

  1. Chargez le fichier GCode dans l’imprimante et lancez l’impression.
  2. Récupérez les objets à la fin de l’impression.

Mise en œuvre :

1.Nettoyez au liquide vaisselle ou à l’alcool vos impressions pour y enlever les microbes et les traces éventuelles de colle. Laissez sécher.
2.Choisissez une ou plusieurs lettres à colorer. Appliquez un masque autour a l’aide de scotch et de papier.
3.Appliquer le colorant en bombe. Retirez le masque. Si le colorant a « baver » vous pouvez essuyer les bavures avec un pinceau/chiffon imbibé d’eau. Comme le colorant est alimentaire, il se dissout avec l’eau.

  1. Appliquez le tampon « HP » sur le gâteau.
    5.Remplissez le fond de l’empreinte du tampon avec le colorant alimentaire et un pinceau. (Aspergez le fond d’une petite assiette pour récupérer le colorant de la bombe et y tremper votre pinceau.)
    6.Piquez le texte dans votre gâteau.
    7.Ajoutez des accessoires et les bougies. Pour ma part, j’ai réalisé un balai avec de la pâte à sucre marron et un vif d’or avec une boule en chocolat plantée sur un cure dent ( les décors sont réalisés avec une poche à douille et du chocolat fondu), des feuilles squelette pour les ailes, le tout recouvert de colorant Or en bombe.

Régalez vous …

title: Fisher Delta Optical Axis endstop for Gen7

description.text:
This is a mod to upgrade the original axis endstop micro-switch (+/-0.1mm) with a gen7 type optical encoder (+/-0.015mm). These are pretty cheap off ebay ( £7per 3off at time of writing).
The tab is fixed to the carriage & breaks the beam of the optical switch. It is long enough to work with the slight overtravel during the Fisher datum routine.
I printed the blocks in pla & friction welded them in place with pla filament & dremmel. The endstop is screwed into the holes in the block using wood screws. The tabs are centred with unit raised & stuck in place with some fletching adhesive ( I haven't got round to spin welding them ).
The endstop pins are bent & soldered so the fixed cable is routed out of the way of the Bowden tube.
The switch type is S1 in the config.
To set the XYZ axis offsets in the config file you will go though the normal iterative process (using the measuring macro & subtracting the errors from the previous config offsets). It is stable once done.
NB Existing micro-switches only use 2 wires ( switching Ground ) new 3rd wire is the +3v supply.

title: Micro Quadcopter 105mm 110mm FPV Scisky
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is another variation of a 105mm or 110mm FPV quad for a Scisky v1.2 flight controller. The Micro 105 FPV Quadcopter - 8.5mm Motors, Micro Scisky by Punkkills and Micro 105-remix for HYPERION MINI FPV CAMERA by lpoc78 are declared as remix sources to provide credit to design influences. No digital source was actually used from either design. A heavily commented openSCAD source script is provided to enable user tailoring.

The baseline design leverages the following key components -

  • 8.5mm x 20mm brushed motors (Racerstar, Sidewinder, etc.)
  • 55 or 56mm props like those for Walkera QR Ladybird
  • FX797T or Hyperion MiniCam Camera and VTX All-In-One
  • Scisky v1.2 flight controller with DSMX receiver, updated to Cleanflight v1.14.2
  • Pololu U3V12F5 5v regulator for AIO power
  • Turnigy NanoTech 500mAh 1S battery

I used the DSM2/DSMX version of the Scisky v1.2 board that is commonly available. The Scisky v2.1 boards with STM32 F3 processors also fit. The v1.2 and v2.1 boards have two rows of pads and a single connector that are meant for use in a overskyrc VTX solution. Compatibility with the older style Scisky with UART and II2C connectors is unknown - the possible issue is whether there are components on the bottom side of the earlier boards that interfere with the board supports in the tray. The F3 version of the board, as well as variations with Devo, Futaba, Frysky, Flysky and Hubsan compatible receivers are available from http://www.overskyrc.com/.

There have been problems with the 5V regulator on the original Scisky boards handling the VTX load, so I used a standalone Pololu 5V regulator like many have. I've noticed the F3 version of the new Scisky is described at OverskyRC has having a 1-amp 5V output instead of 500mAh. Maybe the F3 boards have a new regulator design that reduces the need for the Pololu.

The frame design leverages three-dimensional sweeping arcs intended to provide a compromise between strength and weight. The Scisky flight controller mounts to a small tray that is vibration isolated from the frame using foam tape. The battery is strapped to a smaller plate that mounts above the frame.

The design is parameter driven. Component parameters allow the components to be previewed in their installed locations. A small test plate can be created for fit-checking hardware and the motors before printing a complete frame.

Various options are built into the openSCAD script. The provided STL includes options for the protective arc in front of the AIO, rubber band mounts for use with the AIO, and provision for a rollbar fabricated from 1/8-inch polycarbonate rod. Precut rods are available at http://picnicquads.com/product/roll-bars/, or rods can be cut from item 2XPT9 rod at http://www.grainger.com. The provided STL has the AIO mounted at 7-degree angle, front-to-rear motor spacing of 80mm, side-to-side motor spacing of 76mm (110mm diagonal size).

The gallery photo shows the frame printed in Voltivo Excelfil Signal Orange PLA, which is a near-perfect color match to the orange QR Ladybird propellers. The three frame components for the provided STL weighed in at 11.3g, for a full AUW of 57.7g.

Those not wanting to bother with FPV can just not install the all-in-one and Pololu.

See the openSCAD script for more information. Introductory comments offer suggestions on how to proceed with tailoring.

For information on the frame evolution or information on a quad build using this frame, see the forum thread at http://intofpv.com/t-first-fpv-quad-build.

Printer:

MakerFarm i3v

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Infill:

Worry more about perimeters and slicer gap fill settings - there is very little infill volume

Notes:

Test prints of the frame were printed on a MakerFarm i3v variation of a Prusa i3 with a 0.40mm nozzle, using Simplify 3D as the slicer. Simplify3D was set for 0.20mm layer height, auto extrusion width, 30% triangular infill, 2 solid top and bottom layers, and 3 perimeters printed outside-in. Takes about 4.5 meters of 1.75mm filament and less than an hour to print the frame components.

Print the test plate first for fit checking mounting screws for the battery plate, the rollbar (optional), and a motor. See the test_plate module in the openSCAD script for suggestions on what to look for in the fit check, and for hints on what parameters to adjust if something doesn't fit.

Those that plan to crash the quad into hard objects may opt to print in ABS. I preferred the rigid form of PLA. Print cooling airflow was applied shortly after the first few layers were printed.

I coated the inside of the motor mount holes with liquid electrical tape to provide improved grip on the motors. The battery shelf is also coated with liquid electrical tape to provide the battery with a nonslip surface. Following an idea from the Oscar Liang blog, subminiature zip ties have been added to the motor mounts to help them retain long-term shape with motor heating. Self-adhesive felt pads were added for protection under each motor. Combinations of dental bands and hair bands are used for battery and AIO mounting. Narrow strips of 3M VHB (Very High Bond) tape were used on the bottom of the FC tray. Wires were dressed along the frame using dental floss threaded through small holes drilled into the frame ridge.

What is a pogo jig? It's a tool to make electronic prototypes. Read more about this pogo project https://medium.com/@hlchlc/take-your-pogo-jig-to-the-next-level-c016b483d6fc#.6s2gyaqf8

We are sharing 3 elements towards a successful pogo pin jig.

  1. A needle pogo pin
  2. A pogo pin tolerance
  3. A rim for pogo insertion clearance

How to use this model:
A. Place the pogo pin model and the tolerance in your design
B. Align them concentrically and flushed to the bottom of the pogo pin.
C. Make a pogo support volume, positioned right below the head of the pogo pin
D. Place 2 rims on both sides of the pogo support
E. Use the rim and pogo pin tolerance to carve out the pogo support volume

There, you just made a holder to place a pogo pin.

We included the rims in the design because sometimes, the printer can smear on the pogo pin entry points. When that happens, the smear obstructs insertion. The rims are needed on both sides of the pogo support, providing a smooth entry.

For clarification, there are 2 additional elements for reference (not for printing).
I. Pogo bed with a via
II. Pogo support

Your pogo bed board may be thicker or thinner (Ours is 1.8mm). In that case, make sure the bottom of pogo bed aligns with the bottom of the pogo pins, and more importantly, adjust/scale the vias.

We'd love to know how you make your own pogo jigs. Don't hesitate to leave us a comment when you did!

description.text:
This is an Y tensioner module that fits Anet A2, Tevo Tarantula and possibly other printers that are using 2040 extrusion on Y axis.

Inspired by Banholm's Tarantula Y tensioner http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1704100, but I didn't like the size of it... it's HUGE. So I went on to create my own, more compact version, which doesn't share any parts with Banholm's.
The sideplates are same height and just 10mm longer than A2 stock sides (72 vs 82 mm). It has 10mm of adjustment, which is plenty for me.

Printer:

Anet A2

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.2

Infill:

70

Notes:

I printed all the parts with 70% infill and was happy with the results, so didn't try any other options :) With correct orientation all the parts should print fine without supports.

To assemble this, you need 6 pcs of M4x10 or M4x12 screws, one M4x30 bolt with 7mm head and one M4 nut for tensioning, and 6-8 M4x10 bolts+T-nuts for mounting it to the 2040 frame. If you want to use M5 bolts/T-nuts, print with thicker walls (min 1.2) and drill the relevant holes with 5mm drill, should work fine.
UPDATE: Don't use the cheap chinese 16t idler pulleys, they will not last.I'm using 16t idlers in the tensioner, but original flanged 623 bearings would work fine as well. Use the original flanged bearings with a 0.5mm shim between the bearings, otherwise they are too narrow for 6mm belt. Original M3x30mm screws can be used for the idlers, only thing is that they must NOT be tightened, the bearings/idlers must be able to rotate freely, so I suggest using M3 nyloc nuts, 2 standard nuts tightened against each other or a drop of threadlock to prevent loosening over time. I used nyloc nuts.
Easiest is to assemble the inner slide first, then backplate + nut (loosely), then add the sides and mount the whole assembly to the frame.

title: Filament guide for passing through a material (such as wood)
license: Creative Commons - Attribution - Non-Commercial - Share Alike

description.text:
This is yet another filament guide for passing filament through materials, such as wood. An example of how it is used is shown in the photos. :)

It allows for a PTFE teflon tube and PC4-M6 fitting to be installed (http://a.co/iF4gXMz) as seen in the photos. A hole can be made in the material ("wood" - in my case) just larger than the size of the filament guide, and then the guide can insert right into the material and act as a passageway. It's imperative, in my opinion, to use a filament guide of some sort to limit the amount of debris on the filament.

I remixed this from the Ikea Lack Printer Enclosure cable guide (by LKM) and the JG Aurora A3 Filament guide (by copermen).

I'm currently using it on my Ikea Lack printer enclosure (which I haven't posted quite yet, since I'm still working on sealing the printer in).

description.text:
This is simply an X carriage foo the fantastic Hybercube printer by Tech2C.

This item is remix of the hypercube carriage remix proposed by arturslab (capitve nut locks).

My contribution:

  • redefined the mounting holes to be compatible with prusa i3 rework (M4 holes, 23mm horizontal and vertical spacing) to reuse a lot of existing mounting for extruders and hotends. There are 3 out of 4 holes due to limitations in the carriage. Those should be more than enough.

  • reinforced both belt clamps

Freecad added for reference and further remix. I warn you that the item has been created converting the STL into a mesh and then into a solid.
Boolean operations on such solid may lead to missing faces. In that case, recreate the faces from edges and seelct them with the "solid" to export a valid STL.
Doing that, item does print correctly.

Edit: March, 8, 2017:
Added a version with nutlock for 4mm screws since I've found that it may be quite difficult to mount the hotend otherwise when the carriage will be in place:)

description.text:
Hello.

I was looking for a cryptex that is somewhat fancy and with customize password. Didn't find any that I liked so I made one myself in Autodesk Inventor 2016 (best 3d modeling software in my opinion).

This cryptex is made so that the password is "IronMan". You could switch the letters and create some other password, but i never tried. However, if you want different letters, like "B" or whatever, just let me know in the comments, I'll upload it ASAP.

For this specific one you'll need:

  • all letters x1 each
  • closing ring x2
  • handle left top x1
  • handle left bottom x1
  • handle right top x1
  • handle right bottom x1

Unfortunately, I did not manage to make both handles identical, but they are super alike.

After you print all parts necessary, you'll need to glue some things.
Take "Handle Left Top" and put the "Closing Ring" on it so that the arrow points outside of the handle, right above the cut out slot. Glue them together.
Next, put all the letters on in the desirable order, put the last "Closing Ring" on so that the arrow points to the letters, right above the slot. Glue the ring to the tube.
Lastly, glue the "Handles" together, right to right and left to left.
Now it should be all together. you can try if it all fits nicely.

If you have any questions, put them in the comments. I'll answer ASAP.

Thank you.

I used XYZ Printing DaVinci 1.0 as my printer. Came out pretty good on excellent settings but still needed some cleaning up after finished. 
To make it best, I recommend high percentage of infill, for better rigidity and stiffness. It'll make it nice and strong.
Designing it, I had a general idea but no set vision so that is what i came up with.

title: Bed camera mount for Makergear M2

description.text:
This is a bed camera mount for the Makergear M2. I designed it, originally, to use with a Raspberry Pi camera inside this case: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1646474 . I redesigned it to be a little more general by using a tripod-screw mount with a threaded ball mount for the Pi camera case. Now, you can use it with any camera with a tripod mount. Still, you'd be better off using the low-mass Pi camera.

If you're careful, you can mount the camera directly on the bed mount. That's the way I did it. For a while. Then I was rudely reminded that the part-cooling fan may smash into whatever you mount there should your printer move the hot end out near Z0,Y0,X200. The quickly-designed extension arm will help keep the camera out of harms' way. It has serrations to match the bed mount and will lock the camera at your selected position.

To install the camera mount, you will need to remove the rubber corner piece (shown sitting on the bed in one of the photos. Save it somewhere.) Slide the camera mount over the bed's aluminum foot - it should be a snug fit. Replace the M3 screws. The existing ones should work.

Select the parts you want for your configuration and assemble. Remember that the bed will go up 250mm and you'll need enough slack in the camera cable. If using the Pi camera, you can use the cable hangers to help manage the ribbon cable. Note that one of the hangers has nubs to help restrict the cable movement in order to keep the cable movement from moving the camera.

There are 3 lengths of screws - the longer one will be handy if you use the ribbon cable hangers.

I've included one STL that is a plate of the complete set (with an extra nut.) This is for convenience, though you may be better served by only printing what you will need for your particular configuration.

Credits:

I used mike_mattala's Nut Job (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:193647) for the screws and nuts, with some slight modifications to make the knurled screw. This is an excellent tool for making nuts and bolts and the way he generates the threads makes the result very easy to slice and print successfully.

I originally used Exclusive (Austin Trulove)'s Pi camera mount and case (link, above) with my Prusa i3 Mk2 and I liked the way it worked. When it came time to "Pi" up my M2, this was the only case I considered.

Finally, a disclaimer of sorts:
I designed the mount using the specs of my M2 printer, which is an early model with a 3-point bed leveling system. My mount wraps the front-right aluminum bed foot - if that foot has changed on subsequent M2 versions, please let me know.

There is a one-layer support printed in the two bed mount screw holes to allow the recessed head area to be printed flat. Cut, drill, or punch this layer out after printing.

Note that the small openings in the mount where the M3 screw heads are recessed are normal. You can see them in the photos, but they are not actually in the STL or Preview . They will very likely show up when sliced. The screw heads are still enclosed and should not contact the glass.

This is a bench top organizer for small spools of wire or solder. I have a ton of them all over the place and the get unruly. This is my attempt at organizing them all in the same place.
The 'axles' are offset in hopes of preventing the spools from colliding with one another. 
The top of the box has a crude metric ruler without markings. I'd love to make this better. 
This box is cut from 3mm plywood. I use Luau wood because a giant sheet of it costs $10 and they cut it down into laserbed sized pieces. (What is with people uploading designs that don't include material width? Or filetypes of proprietary software for that matter?).
The Axle holes are 5mm diameter to accomodate this 5mm(ish) aluminum stock I picked up at the local hobby shop for $2.
This is all rendered from openscad so please give me feedback on material width/axle size and I will glady provide the dxf's.

1) Cut pieces. Save little square hole pieces from the front panel.
2) Assemble the box. I use tape to hold the box together and then glue the joints from the inside. I notice (atleast on my machines) at 3mm material you end up with a slight bit of material loss in the teeth that prevent them from holding together as firmly as you'd like. This shouldn't be as apparent in thicker materials).
3) Use a few of the square pieces you saved as a brace for the back panel to screw in hinges. Again this isn't necessary but a nice thing to do when your material is so thin.
4) Insert 'axles'/wire spools close box and enjoy. This is my first thing! I'm quickly becoming obsessed with openscad and useful creation. I would really appreciate feedback on how this can be made better or maybe things you'd like to see me attempt.

Adding Holes

I added holes to this with the normal spacing of a Tetrix beam. I deiced to make the axis hole be lined up with one side rather than being misaligned and contiguous (i did this for mounting integrity)
